<br>
&quot;If you went with the light side, you'd basically be insane to ever want to group with an evil.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nothing could be further from the truth.  There are MANY legitimate reasons for personalities of different ethos (good/evil, law/discord) to assist each other, even for long periods of time - and this is true in RL as well as fantasy/sci-fi roleplay.<br>
<br>
Ever heard the quotes &quot;My enemy's enemy is my friend.&quot;?  Or how about &quot;The means justify the end.&quot;?  Or perhaps &quot;We're doing this for the greater good (or evil).&quot;<br>
<br>
Fantasy and Sci-Fi literature are chock full of interesting alliances between characters of vastly opposing moral and ethical alignments:  <br>
<br>
Drizzt Do'Urden and Artemis Entriri basically fought back-to-back at one point, <br>
<br>
Raistlin was always at odds with the rest of his group in the Dragonlance saga, however they helped each other constantly, <br>
<br>
Kelemvor travelled with Cyric (in that series of Forgotten Realms books) even though half the time he wanted to kill him, <br>
<br>
Frodo and Samwise accepted Gollem into their travelling party because it served the greater good, <br>
<br>
I don't know how many times members of the Federation cooperated with the Klingons in order to stave off another enemy...<br>
<br>
Merlin knew that Morgan LeFey was ambitious, corrupt and evil but he still tutored her as it served a grand purpose...<br>
<br>
Those types of relationships are what make these genres interesting.<br>
<br>
Also, calling neutrals opportunists is a very shallow analysis of what a true neutral personality really is.  Some neutrals are in fact opportunist mercenaries who don't care for whom they fight as long as the rewards are there.  The true neutral however is something of a selfless servant who must constantly weigh where the scales of balance are shifting and act accordingly.  To do anything but that is to be something other than a true neutral.<br>
<br>
Meow,<br>
<br>
Rexfelix<br>
